Process phase

Replace or drop null values in all dateframe

There are null values in the birthyear column in all four data frames. We will replace those null values with the mean values if the total count of null values is greater than 10% of the total observations. Otherwise, we will remove those observations.

#remove null_values in Q1 dataframe
bike_data_2019_Q1_v2 = bike_data_2019_Q1 %>% drop_na(birthyear)

#finding mean values of birthyear in Q2 and replace with this value
birthyear_Q2_mean <- bike_data_2019_Q2_v2 %>% 
  summarise(mean_birthyear = mean(birthyear, na.rm = TRUE)) %>% 
  pull(mean_birthyear) 

bike_data_2019_Q2_v3 <- bike_data_2019_Q2_v2 %>% 
  mutate(birthyear = ifelse(is.na(birthyear), round(birthyear_Q2_mean), birthyear))

#finding mean values of birthyear in Q3 and replace with this value
birthyear_Q3_mean <- bike_data_2019_Q3 %>% 
  summarise(mean_birthyear = mean(birthyear, na.rm = TRUE)) %>% 
  pull(mean_birthyear) 

bike_data_2019_Q3_v2 <- bike_data_2019_Q3 %>% 
  mutate(birthyear = ifelse(is.na(birthyear), round(birthyear_Q3_mean), birthyear))

#remove null_values in Q4 dataframe
bike_data_2019_Q4_v2 = bike_data_2019_Q4 %>% drop_na(birthyear)

Removing outliers

According to above summary statistics, there are some outliers in tripduration column. We will remove the data which is more than 24 hours (86400 seconds) since the bike is only allow to use within 24 hours.

bike_data_2019_v1 <- bike_data_2019 %>% 
  filter(tripduration < 86400)
Analyzing the whole year after removing outliers
The data shows us that
  • The average tripduration for customer is higher than the subscriber
  • The number of users classified as customer is lower than the number of subscriber
  • The average tripduration is higher in weekends

  mutate(age = 2019-birthyear)

Removing outliers in age column

Q1 <- quantile(bike_data_2019_v1$age,0.25)
Q3 <- quantile(bike_data_2019_v1$age,0.75)

IQR <- Q3-Q1

lower_bound <- Q1 - 1.5*IQR
upper_bound <- Q3 + 1.5*IQR

bike_data_2019_v1 <- subset(bike_data_2019_v1, age >= lower_bound& age <= upper_bound)

Number of Bike Usages by User Type Across Age Group

Conclusion

Let’s go back and answer our initial business task, which is to find how annual members (subscribers) and casual riders (customers) use Cyclistic bikes differently.
According to our analysis and visualization, we can conclude the following:
  • Although the average trip duration for customers is higher compared to subscribers, the number of customers that used the bike is lower than that of subscribers.
  • Subscribers used the bike mostly on weekdays compared to customers, but customers used them more on weekends than subscribers.
  • We can observe that subscribers predominantly use the bikes at 8 AM and 5 PM, indicating peak usage during typical work hours. Subscribers are more likely to use them for work.
  • Around ages 35 and 36, the number of bike usages is significantly higher. For subscribers, the number of bike usages is higher between ages 24 and 32.

Recommendation

To turn Customers into Subscribers:
  1. Since most customers use the bikes on weekends, we could introduce a new subscription plan that allows them to subscribe only for weekends.
  2. We could target customers aged between 30 and 38 for marketing efforts, as most customers fall within this age range. By focusing marketing efforts on this demographic, we can highlight the benefits of becoming subscribers and encourage them to switch to a subscription model.
  3. Implement special promotions or discounts for weekend trips to encourage more customers to subscribe.
